tional, cultural, and racial divides through family formation and its strong potential for reinforcing the very racial and cultural hierarchies it sought to challenge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAdopted childrenxUnited States. 0aAdopted childrenzUnited States. 0aAdoptionxUnited States. 0aAdoptionzUnited States. 0aAsian AmericansxAsiaxUnited States. 0aAsian Americans. 0aIntercountry adoptionxAsia. 0aIntercountry adoptionxUnited States. 0aIntercountry adoptionzAsia. 0aIntercountry adoptionzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Customs & Traditions.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814717226.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479886388423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479886388/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles